{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἔρως</b>, ωτος, ὁ, <br /> <i>accusative</i> ἔρων for ἔρωτα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Alexander Aetolus Elegiacus 3.12, “Anthologia Graeca” 9.39 (from Musicius)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]: in <i>Epic dialect</i> and Lyric poetry usually <b>ἔρος</b> (which see): (ἕραμαι, ἐράω A):—<b>love,</b> mostly of the sexual passion, θηλυκρατὴς ἔ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 600 (Lyric poetry); ἐρῶσ᾽ ἔρωτ᾽ ἔκδημον 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 32 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἔ. τινός <b>love for</b> one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 433; παίδων 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 67 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: generally, <b>love of</b> a thing, <b>desire for i</b> it, πατρῴας γῆς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 540; δεινὸς εὐκλείας ἔ. [prev. author] “Eu.” 865, etc.; ἔχειν ἔμφυτον ἔρωτα περί τι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 782e; πρὸς τοὺς λόγους 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Nigr.Praef.”; ἔρωτα σχὼν τῆς Ἑλλάδος τύραννος γενέσθαι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.32 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἔ. ἔχει με with <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 521; θανόντι κείνῳ συνθανεῖν ἔρως μ᾽ ἔχει 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 953; αὐτοῖς ἦν ἔρως θρόνους ἐᾶσθαι [prev. author] “OC” 367 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἔ. ἐμπίπτει μοι with <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 341, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 6.24 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; εἰς ἔρωτά τινος ἀφικέσθαι, ἐλθεῖν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Antiphanes Comicus 212.3, 4th c.BC: Anaxilas Comicus 21.5 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: <i>plural</i>, <b>loves, amours,</b> ἀλλοτρίων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 3.30; οὐχ ὅσιοι ἔ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 765 (Lyric poetry); ἔρωτες ἐμᾶς πόλεως 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1316 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], etc.; of dolphins, πρὸς παῖδας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 631a10 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: generally, <b>desires,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 617 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>object of love</b> or <b>desire,</b> ἀπρόσικτοι ἔρωτες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 11.48, compare 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Tim.” 14. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> <b>passionate joy,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 693 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>proper name</i>, <b>the god of love,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Anacreon Lyricus 65, 4th-5th c.BC: Parmenides Poeta Philosophus 13, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 525 (Lyric poetry), etc.; Έ. ἀνίκατε μάχαν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 781 (Lyric poetry): in _plural_, 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 184.3, etc. \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> at Nicaea, a <b>funeral wreath,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" EM 379.54. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> name of the κλῆρος Ἀφροδίτης, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Catalogus Codicum Astrologorum” 1.168 \">Refs</a>]; = third κλῆρος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Paulus Alexandrinus Astrologus “K.” 3 \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]; one of the τόποι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Vettius Valens Astrologus 69.16. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G7513","accentedUnicode":"ἔρως","shortDef":"passion","mediumDef":"passion","stepGloss":"passion","stepTransliteration":"erōs","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}